The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Century buyback price at Rs 122

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT 

 Mumbai, May 9: Century Enka will buy back shares at Rs 122 apiece from Acordis Overseas Investment BV, its non-resident shareholder.

 According to the scheme, Acordis will be entitled to tender up to 30 per cent of its shareholding out of its stake of 38.24 per cent in the company. 

 However, the price offered is at a 28 per cent discount to the closing price of the Century Enka scrip on the Bombay Stock Exchange today. After opening at Rs 156, the Century Enka share rose to an intra-day high of Rs 181 following which it ended at Rs 171.35.

 The decision to come out with a scheme of arrangement to buy back shares from the companys non-resident shareholders was taken at a board meeting last Saturday. 

 Century Enka today informed the stock exchanges that the scheme will be beneficial to the remaining shareholders as it will result in a corresponding increase in book value and earnings per share.

 Promoters directly hold a 13.25 per cent stake in the BK Birla company. The total promoter holding, including that of Grasim Industries, Kesoram Industries Ltd and persons acting in concert, is put at 54.97 per cent. The rest is held by institutional investors at 12.70 per cent, the public at 26.83 per cent, private corporate bodies at 3.94 per cent and NRIs/ OCBs at 1.55 per cent. 

 After its acquisition of Akzo Nobel in December 2000, Acordis had obtained indirect shareholding in Century Enka. 

 Later, the Securities and Exchange Board of India directed Acordis to make an open offer for an additional 20 per cent stake at a price of Rs 114 per share, including interest. 




